WEBVTT

00:03.127 --> 00:05.361
Okay, guys.
Now you try it!

00:06.030 --> 00:07.263
Nice!

00:07.265 --> 00:09.165
Very smooth, Baljeet.

00:10.434 --> 00:12.135
What's the problem, Buford?

00:12.137 --> 00:14.103
Why, you know,
the sun was in my eyes.

00:14.105 --> 00:15.972
Buford, what's with
the lack of effort?

00:15.974 --> 00:17.974
I'm just trying
to be careful.
You?

00:17.976 --> 00:20.243
Yeah, we're out of credit
at the emergency room.

00:20.245 --> 00:22.412
My mom said
if I break one more bone,

00:22.414 --> 00:24.213
she's gonna break
the rest of 'em.

00:24.215 --> 00:26.082
Fairly sure that was
hyperbole.

00:26.084 --> 00:28.184
Besides, look how hard
that hydrant is.

00:28.186 --> 00:32.155
Well, maybe we could make
our own fire hydrants
out of soft foam rubber.

00:32.157 --> 00:33.589
Hey! That's a great idea!

00:33.591 --> 00:36.225
Ferb, I know
what we're gonna do today.

00:36.527 --> 00:37.827
Seriously?

00:37.829 --> 00:40.096
That's it? A soft fire plug?

00:40.098 --> 00:42.832
Well, yeah. Attached to
a giant revolving treadmill

00:42.834 --> 00:46.002
with a giant
soft neighborhood,
containing soft obstacles.

00:46.004 --> 00:47.070
Oh, yeah, okay.

00:47.304 --> 00:48.604
Where is Perry?

00:48.606 --> 00:49.872
What did you say?

00:49.874 --> 00:51.341
I was just asking
where Perry is.

00:51.343 --> 00:52.442
Oh.

00:52.876 --> 00:54.110
What did you
think I said?

00:54.112 --> 00:55.410
Uh, well,
I thought you said...

00:55.412 --> 00:57.446
Uh, never mind.
It was too weird.

01:20.571 --> 01:21.871
(MONOGRAM GRUNTING)

01:21.873 --> 01:23.406
(GROANING)

01:23.408 --> 01:24.406
<i>Get it off! Ugh!</i>

01:24.408 --> 01:27.243
<i>Sorry, Agent P,</i>
<i>I just walked through</i>
<i>a spider web.</i>

01:27.345 --> 01:28.443
Don't you just hate that?

01:28.445 --> 01:31.047
You spend the rest of the day
worried there's
a spider on you.

01:31.149 --> 01:32.547
(SHUDDERS)
<i>Gives me the willies.</i>

01:32.549 --> 01:36.552
Any-hoo, our sources tell us
that there's a cowboy hat
in front of Doof's building.

01:36.554 --> 01:38.454
Normally, that wouldn't be
of any interest to us,

01:38.456 --> 01:40.990
because this is the week
of the Danville Hootenanny,

01:40.992 --> 01:43.926
But it's a rather large hat,
and, in spite of its name,

01:43.928 --> 01:47.029
the Danville Hootenanny
<i>is a dignified affair.</i>

01:47.031 --> 01:48.329
<i>I wish I had more information,</i>

01:48.331 --> 01:51.534
<i>but Carl said there</i>
<i>was a big bee by the</i>
<i>surveillance equipment.</i>

01:51.536 --> 01:53.936
So, get out there, Agent P.

01:53.938 --> 01:56.572
(SHUDDERS)   <i>Carl, is...</i>
<i>Is there a spider on my head?</i>

01:56.574 --> 01:59.175
CARL:   <i>No, sir.</i>
<i>There's no spider</i>

01:59.177 --> 02:00.075
<i>on your head.</i>

02:00.077 --> 02:02.912
NARRATOR:   <i>Meanwhile, at the</i>
<i>Danville Space Laboratory...</i>

02:02.914 --> 02:04.414
"Laboratory"?

02:04.416 --> 02:07.216
(GRUNTING IN FRUSTRATION)

02:07.618 --> 02:10.520
Oh, Jack, it sure was
nice of you to show
Candace and me around.

02:10.522 --> 02:12.588
This satellite stuff
is very interesting.

02:12.590 --> 02:13.488
No problem, Linda.

02:13.490 --> 02:16.159
I'm flattered
you'd be interested
in our humble facility,

02:16.161 --> 02:18.161
considering your background
in astrophysics.

02:18.163 --> 02:20.196
Oh, yeah. Uh, listen,
that's kind of a secret.

02:20.198 --> 02:21.364
So don't...
Oh! Oh, I'm sorry.

02:21.498 --> 02:22.897
So, what does
your father do here?

02:22.899 --> 02:26.335
Oh, he's part of a team
that makes and manages
reconnaissance satellites.

02:26.337 --> 02:29.372
They actually had
a couple of rovers on Mars
earlier this summer.

02:29.374 --> 02:31.140
But they suddenly
stopped working.

02:31.142 --> 02:33.075
You wouldn't know
anything about that,
would you?

02:33.077 --> 02:36.012
Uh, how would I, uh...
(CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY)
What do you mean?

02:36.014 --> 02:37.680
All right, Your Highness.

02:37.682 --> 02:39.115
(GASPS) Who told?

02:39.117 --> 02:40.015
Stacy.

02:40.017 --> 02:44.053
CHORUS:   <i>♪ Doofenshmirtz</i>
<i>Evil Incorporated! ♪</i>

02:44.155 --> 02:46.689
Uh, Perry the Platypus,
I bet you're wondering

02:46.691 --> 02:49.158
wondering why I'm cowering
outside my lab.

02:49.160 --> 02:51.027
Well, the day started
like any other day.

02:51.029 --> 02:54.130
You know, I,
"How am I going to take over
the Tri-State Area," but...

02:54.132 --> 02:58.000
And I suddenly remembered
a movie that I'd seen
long ago at a drive-in.

02:58.002 --> 02:59.969
<i>It was called</i>
<i>Night of the Felis.</i>

03:00.137 --> 03:03.005
<i>I knew right away</i>
<i>that the old masters</i>
<i>were onto something.</i>

03:03.007 --> 03:07.577
Imagine, taking something cute
and enlarging it
to frightening proportions.

03:08.145 --> 03:09.144
<i>Brilliant!</i>

03:09.146 --> 03:10.944
<i>But in order to take over</i>
<i>the Tri-State Area,</i>

03:10.946 --> 03:14.250
<i>I'd have to start with some</i>
<i>other type of small animals.</i>
<i>(PEOPLE IN MOVIE SCREAMING)</i>

03:14.252 --> 03:16.719
<i>Preferably something</i>
<i>that could fly.</i>
<i>(CATS IN MOVIE MEWLING)</i>

03:16.721 --> 03:18.621
<i>And I vowed to get</i>
<i>right to work,</i>

03:18.623 --> 03:20.990
<i>as soon as the movie was over.</i>

03:20.992 --> 03:24.427
The first thing I needed to do
was create an inator
that would make things larger.

03:24.429 --> 03:25.294
Huh?

03:25.296 --> 03:27.997
<i>I tried it out</i>
<i>on my cowboy hat.</i>

03:31.201 --> 03:32.200
<i>It was a success.</i>

03:32.202 --> 03:35.404
<i>My ten-gallon hat</i>
<i>had turned into</i>
<i>a two thousand-gallon hat.</i>

03:35.406 --> 03:36.472
Whoa!

03:36.640 --> 03:38.074
(CRASHING)
(CAR ALARM WAILING)

03:38.475 --> 03:39.774
Well, that's the end
of that hat.

03:39.776 --> 03:44.113
<i>Next, I had to</i>
<i>genetically modify a mouse</i>
<i>so it could fly.</i>

03:44.115 --> 03:45.181
(MOUSE SQUEALING)
(BITING)

03:45.183 --> 03:46.081
DOOFENSHMIRTZ: Ow!

03:46.083 --> 03:48.451
<i>Then I decided</i>
<i>it would be easier</i>
<i>to just use a bat.</i>

03:48.453 --> 03:52.188
So, I ordered
a retired stunt bat
from a low-budget bat circus

03:52.190 --> 03:53.523
<i>that had recently gone</i>
<i>belly-up.</i>

03:53.525 --> 03:55.057
<i>You know, the economy.</i>

03:55.059 --> 03:58.127
I was on the precipice
of Tri-State Area domination.

03:58.129 --> 04:01.731
<i>At last, I had</i>
<i>the ultimate creepy soldier!</i>
<i>(SQUEAKS)</i>

04:01.733 --> 04:05.167
<i>And then I remembered,</i>
<i>I had a very mild phobia</i>
<i>of bats.</i>

04:05.169 --> 04:05.967
(BAT SQUEAKING)

04:05.969 --> 04:08.104
(SHRIEKS) Get away,
get away, get away!

04:08.106 --> 04:10.406
<i>I also have a mild phobia</i>
<i>of shellfish.</i>

04:10.408 --> 04:12.041
WAITRESS:
Here's your order, sir.

04:12.043 --> 04:13.709
DOOFENSHMIRTZ: (SHRIEKS)
Get away, get away, get away!

04:14.111 --> 04:15.110
<i>But bats are worse.</i>

04:15.112 --> 04:17.113
Scram, you flying gerbil!
(BAT SQUEAKING)

04:17.115 --> 04:18.180
Am-scray!

04:18.815 --> 04:19.814
(SQUEAKING)

04:19.816 --> 04:22.818
You're making me miss
the Hootenanny!
(SQUEAKING)

04:23.253 --> 04:24.754
Sir, I found your radio.

04:24.756 --> 04:27.123
It was embedded
in the dashboard of your car.

04:27.125 --> 04:30.259
Norm! Don't just stand there!
Do something about this bat!

04:31.061 --> 04:33.563
Really? That's your solution?
Throw a radio at it.

04:33.565 --> 04:36.666
Whoa! Whoa! Whoa!
Don't throw that.
That's imitatable.

04:36.668 --> 04:37.766
What if I hit it with this?

04:37.768 --> 04:40.303
No! No! Wait!
Don't shoot him with that!
That's my...

04:40.305 --> 04:43.239
And I thought the bat
was scary before,
when he was, you know, tiny.

04:43.241 --> 04:45.474
(BAT SHRIEKING MENACINGLY)

04:45.809 --> 04:48.477
It was at that point
that Norm and I decided
to come out here.

04:48.479 --> 04:51.147
Plus the bat kind of
looks like my cousin,
Narthelliot!

04:51.149 --> 04:53.482
Which, as you can imagine,
is weird for me.

04:53.484 --> 04:55.217
Isn't that about right, Norm?

04:55.219 --> 04:57.520
It's even more horrible
than it looks!

04:57.654 --> 04:59.555
PHINEAS: Everybody got
their helmets and boards?

04:59.557 --> 05:01.190
ISABELLA: Yeah!
BUFORD AND BALJEET: I'm ready!

05:01.558 --> 05:02.858
Okay, Ferb, fire it up.

05:02.860 --> 05:04.360
We're going to
Foam Town!

05:06.296 --> 05:07.797
(WHOOPING)

05:10.133 --> 05:11.434
(GRUNTS)

05:11.436 --> 05:15.738
<i>♪ There's nothing</i>
<i>that I've found as good</i>
<i>as goin' round and round</i>

05:15.740 --> 05:17.239
<i>♪ In Foam Town</i>

05:17.641 --> 05:19.108
<i>♪ In Foam Town</i>

05:19.643 --> 05:21.210
<i>♪ I used to skin my knees</i>
<i>(WHOOPING)</i>

